2 students, 2 teachers killed in Ga. high school shooting; teen shooter suspect identified

by TAYLOR FISHMAN | The National Desk

Wed, September 4th 2024 at 12:32 PM
Updated Thu, September 5th 2024 at 12:19 PM
28
VIEW ALL PHOTOS
A medical helicopter is seen in front of Apalachee High School after a shooting at the school Wednesday, Sept. 4, 2024, in Winder, Ga. (AP Photo/Mike Stewart)

    TOPICS:

    ShootingGeorgiaHigh schoolCasualtiesApalachee High SchoolLockdownInvestigationSuspect

WINDER, Ga. (TND) Two students and two teachers were killed Wednesday in a shooting at Apalachee High School in Winder, Georgia, according to the Georgia Bureau of Investigation (GBI), with nine others taken to the hospital for gunshot-related wounds.

NEWEST STORY: Law enforcement officials reveal there were red flags before the Georgia school shooting

Authorities identified the victims as the following individuals:

  • Mason Schermerhorn, a 14-year-old student
  • Christian Angulo, a 14-year-old student
  • Richard Aspinwall, a teacher
  • Christina Irimie, a teacher

The Barrow County Sheriff's Office said a suspect was taken into custody, 14-year-old Colt Gray, who is a student at the high school. Gray surrendered once law enforcement got to the scene.

GBI Director Chris Hosey said the teen will be charged with murder and tried as an adult. Authorities believe he acted alone, saying there is no evidence of an accomplice.

In a joint statement from Atlanta's Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI) and the Jackson County Sheriff's Office, authorities said the teen had been interviewed after the FBI received several anonymous tips in May 2023 about online threats to commit an unspecified school shooting.

"The online threats contained photographs of guns. Within 24 hours, the FBI determined the online post originated in Georgia and the FBIs Atlanta Field Office referred the information to the Jackson County Sheriffs Office for action," the statement noted.

The sheriff's office tracked down a potential subject, a then-13-year-old boy, according to the statement. They interviewed the teen and his father, who told authorities he had guns in the home, but added his son "did not have unsupervised access to them."

The statement noted the child denied making the threats, with the sheriff's office warning school to keep an eye on him.

"At that time, there was no probable cause for arrest or to take any additional law enforcement action on the local, state, or federal levels," the statement noted.

Authorities are still looking into how the suspect obtained the gun used in the shooting, as well as how he got it into the school.

During a news conference, Sheriff Jud Smith said the nine people who were hurt are expected to survive. He added that his heart breaks for the community, especially the students and staff.

But I want to make it very clear that hate will not prevail in this county," Smith said. "I want that to be very clear and known. Love will prevail over what happened today.

The high school went on lockdown around 10:20 a.m., with law enforcement responding immediately.

According to the White House, President Joe Biden was informed on the situation.

"President Biden has been briefed by his Homeland Security Advisor, Liz Sherwood-Randall, on the tragic shooting at Apalachee High School in Winder, Georgia and his administration will continue coordinating with federal, state, and local officials as we receive more information.'

Biden later released a statement regarding the shooting to his social media accounts.

Attorney General Merrick Garland said he is devastated for the families affected by the tragedy. He also offered federal support to the local community.

I want to address the tragic shooting that occurred this morning at a high school in Winder, Georgia. We are still gathering information, but the FBI and ATF are on the scene working with state, local and federal partners, Garland said.The Justice Department stands ready to provide any resources or support that the Winder community needs in the days ahead,

The Barrow County Superintendent, Dallas LeDuff, said schools will be closed for the remainder of the week. He added that grief counseling will be available for students.

The FBI said it will dedicate all available resources "to seek justice and bring closure for the victims and their families."

EDITOR'S NOTE: The Associated Press contributed to this report.
